TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Stock Allocation for a Capacitated Supply System
AU  - de Véricourt, Francis
AU  - Karaesmen, Fikri
AU  - Dallery, Yves
Y1  - 2002/11/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.48.11.1486.263
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.48.11.1486.263
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1486
EP  - 1501
VL  - 48
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We consider a capacitated supply system that produces a single item that is demanded by several classes of customers. Each customer class may have a different backorder cost, so stock allocation arises as a key decision problem. We model the supply system as a multi customer make-to-stock queue. Using dynamic programming, we show that the optimal allocation policy has a simple and intuitive structure. In addition, we present an efficient algorithm to compute the parameters of this optimal allocation policy. Finally, for a typical supply chain design problem, we illustrate that ignoring the stock allocation dimension?a frequently encountered simplifying assumption?can lead to incorrect managerial decisions.
AB  - We consider a capacitated supply system that produces a single item that is demanded by several classes of customers. Each customer class may have a different backorder cost, so stock allocation arises as a key decision problem. We model the supply system as a multi customer make-to-stock queue. Using dynamic programming, we show that the optimal allocation policy has a simple and intuitive structure. In addition, we present an efficient algorithm to compute the parameters of this optimal allocation policy. Finally, for a typical supply chain design problem, we illustrate that ignoring the stock allocation dimension?a frequently encountered simplifying assumption?can lead to incorrect managerial decisions.
